      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You raise a compelling moral argument known as the \"asymmetry of risk,\" which suggests that the catastrophic cost of AI failure outweighs the low probability of its occurrence, creating an imperative to act preemptively regardless of exact timelines. Proponents of this view hold that ignoring a theoretically possible extinction event would be a severe failure of human responsibility, even if the probability remains low today. However, opponents counter that such heavy-handed regulation might serve as a \"precautionary principle\" gone wrong if it halts progress on technologies that could otherwise yield genuine benefits for current generations. Ultimately, the debate hinges on whether society values mitigating a tiny future risk more than hastening the resolution of many near-term challenges like climate change and poverty.",
